figgy.title: Generate report for any and all Cotsen Items within the Digital Repository

comments.body:
We have a mystery I am unable to solve. Wonder if you could help me and Andrea out there.
We notice that in the **Location** field of a Figgy record, there are two types of displays.

One type shows "Special Collection" and misses Cotsen's location codes, even though they are in the Alma holdings records. (I tried refreshing metadata and it didn't seem to help.)
![image](https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/assets/54282275/25466e56-0cc4-4f60-8c8a-976767b61188)
([9947140843506421](https://figgy.princeton.edu/catalog/c1c755f3-34f3-4c62-b5dd-805d4972d755))

The other type shows the location code as found in holdings record 852$c
![image](https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/assets/54282275/01780d07-59d9-44c1-b4d9-44e4c2f8f704)
([9947470923506421](https://figgy.princeton.edu/catalog/f8e8c4d6-90e1-43cc-991c-300f7b142d40))

Type 1 is a problem. Those records are missing from the report I requested based on location codes. Any thought on what caused this? Thanks!
Minjie

@jpstroop Yes

The following reports were created with #5872 and this script:

```ruby
collection_ids = ["b7e8c42b-6fd0-4cfb-bc6d-b5e5a5c79f5c", "a5454850-8b97-4750-8390-2c5884134f1f"]

years = {
  2021 => DateTime.new(2020,7,1)..DateTime.new(2021,6,30),
  2022 => DateTime.new(2021,7,1)..DateTime.new(2022,6,30),
  2023 => DateTime.new(2022,7,1)..DateTime.new(2023,6,30)
}

years.each do |year, date_range|
  puts "Creating report for #{year}"
  report = ImageReportGenerator.new(collection_ids: collection_ids, date_range: date_range)
  report.write(path: Rails.root.join("tmp", "image-report-#{year}.csv"))
  puts "Created report for #{year}"
end
```

Error when loading works with large number of files

comments.body:
The culprit seems to be that our custom JSON serialization is including a reference to the work for every file in the work. For example, if a work has 3 files the serialization will include 3 files, but each of those 3 files will have a reference back to the work and therefore to the 3 files again. 

For a small number of files this goes unnoticed, but for large number of files (say 2000 files) this becomes a huge problem!

![Screenshot 2023-06-08 at 9 19 21 PM](https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/assets/568286/6e46cdea-792e-47d6-8280-972e88de64bf)

comments.body:
There appears to be a bunch of storage note functionality that's dead code since https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/pull/892
 https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/blob/1a931fdc91178b21e4d5b1a36227d61c42077843/app/models/solr_document.rb#L260-L266

https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/blob/1a931fdc91178b21e4d5b1a36227d61c42077843/app/services/storage_notes.rb

https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/blob/1a931fdc91178b21e4d5b1a36227d61c42077843/config/storage_notes.yml
Note we don't use the 'sca' part of the codes in pulfalight. see https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/pull/1174/files

Implementation note: I'm making a small class for #1154 that can hopefully be used here, too. I imagine we could add to it like `DeliveryNote.new(location).full_note(level: "collection")` where level would be "collection" or "material" and just dropped into the string above which are otherwise identical.
